<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>DDB0133</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">National Institute of Adult Continuing Education – Written evidence</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The National Institute of Adult Continuing Education (NIACE) is an independent charity which promotes adult learning across England and Wales. Through its research, development, publications, events, outreach and advocacy activity, NIACE works to improve the quality and breadth of opportunities available for all adults so they can benefit from learning throughout their lives. NIACE welcomes the opportunity to contribute to the work of the Joint Committee</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">This submission focuses only on those clauses directly affecting learning for adults. The relevant parts of the Bill are:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Clause 3: English Apprenticeships: simplification</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 84.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Schedule 1: Approved English apprenticeships</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Clause 31: Abolition of office of Chief Executive of Skills Funding</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 84.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Schedule 12: Abolition of Office of the Chief Executive of Skills Funding</span></li></ul><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Clause 32: Further and higher education sectors: reduction of burdens</span></li><ul type="circle" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 84.2pt; padding-left:5.8pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">Schedule 13: Further and higher education: reduction of burdens</span></li></ul></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 3 and Schedule 1</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">NIACE welcomes the intention behind these parts of the Bill which aim to simplify the statutory framework for Apprenticeships in England. Such de-regulation is attractive in principle as apprenticeships are primarily contracts of employment and it is right that they should be flexible and responsive to labour market need. Nevertheless, the current regime gives some assurance of fair treatment and of the education and training quality of apprenticeships. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt"> The proposed changes appear to concentrate considerable discretionary powers in the hands of the Secretary of State. NIACE suggests the Committee may wish to consider how best to ensure appropriate and regular scrutiny by Parliament and by others of how those powers are exercised in practice. While Parliament and the National Audit Office have important roles to play, NIACE suggests that there may also be a need for some form of standing advisory committee through which the Secretary of State and officials can he held to account by external stakeholders in the apprenticeship process (employers, trade unions, apprentices and training providers) to ensure public money is well-spent and that quality is maintained.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 31 and Schedule 12</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The abolition of the Office of the Chief Executive of Skills Funding as a statutory post has the effect of bringing the current Skills Funding Agency closer to the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills. There are arguments that this will improve efficiency and responsiveness but once again, it has the effect of concentrating powers in the hands of the Secretary of State.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">If the statutory post is to be abolished, NIACE urges the committee to consider how best to ensure that the Skills Funding Agency is scrutinised and held to account for some £4 billion of further education and skills funding in England each year. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">NIACE believes that there is a strong case for Parliament to establish a statutory expert committee to advise the Secretary of State on the delivery of the Government’s policies in this arena. This should include representatives of employers and employees, local government and providers of education and training and should operate transparently.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Clause 32 and Schedule 13</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">NIACE does not support proposals in Schedule 13 for the de-regulation of qualification requirements for teaching staff and principals in further education and believes that this measure will have an adverse impact on learners.  While recognising that non-qualified instructors can also deliver good teaching and training, the requirement that teaching staff be qualified is an important part of quality assurance for learners. The aspiration for the sector should be that staff are ‘dual professionals’, qualified both in teaching and in their vocational specialism and that they also undertake regular continuing professional development </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14pt; padding-left:4pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">The government has already (via secondary legislation) removed requirements for teachers and trainers in the FE and skills sector to obtain teaching qualifications and this measure would remove the relevant primary legislation contained in the Education Act which allows Ministers to regulate what qualifications FE teachers and trainers should have. In effect, this makes it more difficult for the re-introduction of statutory regulations on teacher qualification requirements in the future. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">NIACE would be pleased to elaborate on anything in this submission. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">13 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Gill Sans MT'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>